        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1518461704" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7006956594910320172"><b>3.75 STARS</b><br/><br/>This story takes place in 19th century London where women can’t vote, work and really don’t have many rights. <br/><br/>Some would classify Lilly Linton as a feminist; I’d say she was a strong, determined and intelligent heroine. Her POV was witty, funny – at times, her inner dialogue had me chuckling. Lilly finds employment with Rikkard Ambrose, a powerful, silent and direct man, provided she disguises herself as a man.<br/><br/>This tale unfolds as these two work together and a letter goes missing that </span>
  <span id="freeText7006956594910320172" style="display:none"><b>3.75 STARS</b><br /><br />This story takes place in 19th century London where women can’t vote, work and really don’t have many rights. <br /><br />Some would classify Lilly Linton as a feminist; I’d say she was a strong, determined and intelligent heroine. Her POV was witty, funny – at times, her inner dialogue had me chuckling. Lilly finds employment with Rikkard Ambrose, a powerful, silent and direct man, provided she disguises herself as a man.<br /><br />This tale unfolds as these two work together and a letter goes missing that Mr. Ambrose is desperate to find. This was well written and these two characters were interesting however, I found the story dragged at times with some repetition and lengthy prose. There is also a bit of romance but it’s not front and centre. Still, this was a refreshing story and I must say, it ends on a cliffhanger. <br /><br />**ARC generously provided by author in exchange for an honest review.**</span>
